<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-11-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="638" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">422.11 G 93/1326</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bading</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-11-06"><hi rend="italic">November 6,
                                1924</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 402</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The receipt is acknowledged of your
                            despatch No. 394 dated September 29, 1924, concerning your conversation
                            with the Minister of Hacienda with a view to bringing about payments on
                            the Guayaquil and Quito Railway bonds.</p>
                        <pb facs="0814" n="700" xml:id="pg_700"/>
                        <p>The Department approves of your action and desires to commend you for the
                            energy and effectiveness with which you have handled this matter.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph
                                    C. Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>